The Indonesian Boeing crashed without an explosion.
The Lion Air Boeing 737 crashed on October 29 after hitting the sea at high speed.
Surjanto Tanjono, head of the Indonesian National Committee for Transport Safety, denied the possibility of an explosion on board the plane.
According to the experts, the engine was running at full power when the plane crashed into the sea, according to the information obtained from the information recording device ("black box") on the crew board.
The report also examined the situation of the aircraft debris in the water.
The aircraft crashed into a region with a radius of 500 meters.
A Boeing 737 of the Indonesian Lion Air company was flying from Jakarta to Pankalpining.
The plane disappeared from radar 13 minutes after takeoff and crashed into the Java Sea between Sumatra and West Java.
All 189 people on board were killed.
The "black box" of the plane was found on November 1.
The rescue team is looking for a second device that can record the crew's words.
The cause of the crash is not yet known.
The aircraft was built in 2018.
